\newlabel{fig:fixed-interface-inversion}{{1}{2}{Offline model selection need not transfer through a fixed decision interface. Panel A shows the selection-transfer setting: models are ranked by an offline validation score, passed through the same fixed decision interface, and evaluated by deployed utility under friction. Panel B reports aggregate offline-selected and deployed-utility winners across representative task families and friction levels. Arrows show offline-selected model \(\rightarrow \) deployed-utility winner; counts denote evaluation units in which the offline-selected model is deployed-suboptimal. Gray zero-friction cells are included for completeness rather than interpreted as friction-causal anchors; the clean zero-friction anchors are the synthetic sanity row in Table~\ref {tab:deployed-selection-report-card} and the Traffic-Hourly Top-\(k\) zero-friction cell}{figure.caption.1}{}}
\newlabel{tab:deployed-selection-report-card}{{1}{3}{Offline-to-deployed selection-transfer report card. Each row fixes a task family, decision interface, and friction level, then asks whether the model selected by the offline validation score remains the deployed-utility winner after the same interface is applied. ``Offline sel.'' denotes the offline-selected model; ``Deploy winner'' denotes the best model under deployed utility; ``Transfer'' is the fraction of evaluation units where the offline-selected model also wins under deployed utility. ``Subopt.'' reports deployed-suboptimal share/count; intervals are paired-bootstrap intervals for the mean deployed shortfall}{table.caption.2}{}}
